@ENDNODE
@NODE TOOLBAR "Toolbar"

                         @{b}@{fg shine} Toolbar icons@{fg text} @{ub}(from left)

  @{" Place track    " LINK TOOLBAR_TRACKS}
  @{" Place pad      " LINK TOOLBAR_PADS}
  @{" Grids settings " LINK TOOLBAR_GRIDS}

@ENDNODE
@NODE TOOLBAR_TRACKS "Toolbar icon - place track"
                    
@{b}1. Place track. @{ub}

After clicking on this icon You can place tracks on the PCB. Currently  only
one layer is available. When You move the pointer on edit area,  You'll  can
see a circle. Its diameter is equal to track width. Click LMB once to  start
track drawing. Now You can  see  an  outline  of  the  track  following  the
pointer. Click LMB again to place a section of track. You can place as  many
sections, as You want.  To  end  the  track  doubleclick  LMB  placing  last
section,  or  press  @{"SPACE" LINK SHORTCUTS}  on  the  keyboard.  The   difference  is   that
doubleclicking allows You to start next track immediately, but  using  SPACE
switches 'place track' mode off. This icon has also a @{"keyboard shortcut" LINK SHORTCUTS}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE TOOLBAR_PADS "Toolbar icon - place pad"

@{b}2. Place pad. @{ub}

Using this icon You can place soldering pads on the  PCB.  In  this  version
only one kind of pads is available. They are rounded (75 @{"mils" LINK GLOSSARY} diameter) with
30 @{"mils" LINK GLOSSARY} hole. When the pointer is on the edit area You can see an outline of
the pad. Click the LBM to place it. To leave 'place pad' mode  select  other
mode in toolbar, click 'place pad' icon again or press  @{"SPACE" LINK SHORTCUTS}  on  keyborad.
This icon has also a @{"keyboard shortcut" LINK SHORTCUTS}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE TOOLBAR_GRIDS "Toolbar icon - adjust grids"

@{b}3. Adjust grids. @{ub}

Click this icon to pop up a grid settings window. You  can  choose  snap and
visible grid value from pop-up list or type it into string gadgets. Grid can
vary from 1 to 9999 @{"mils" LINK GLOSSARY}. With checkmark You can toggle visible grid on and
off. 'Use' button confirms new settings. To cancel press toolbar icon again.
This icon has also a @{"keyboard shortcut" LINK SHORTCUTS}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE MENUS
                                   @{fg shine}@{b} Menus@{fg text}@{ub}

@{u}@{fg shine} Project @{uu}@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg fill}About:@{fg text}
@{ub}Displays "About program" window.
 
@{b}@{fg fill}About MUI:@{ub}@{fg text}
Standard "About MUI" window.

@{b}@{fg fill}Quit:@{fg text}@{ub}
Quits the program.

@{fg shine}@{u} Preferences @{uu}

@{b}@{fg fill}Display:@{fg text}@{ub}
Shows "Display preferences" window. Here You can decide, how PCB will be
displayed on the screen.

@{fg shine}@{b}>@{fg text}@{ub} Scroll with arrows - adjusts scrolling distance, when scrollbars arrows
  are used. 

@{fg shine}@{b}>@{fg text}@{ub} Magnify step - controlls magnify button. Displayed value is a magnify
  factor for single clicking on magnify button.

@{fg shine}@{b}>@{fg text}@{ub} Drawing modes - controlls graphics representation of PCB objects. Possible
  modes are:
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} single lines - tracks are drawn as lines, pads aren't visible,
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} wireframe - only outlines of objects are drawn,
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} filled figures - all objects are filled.
  
@{fg fill}@{b}Layers:@{fg text}@{ub}
Here You can adjust colors of layers. Currently You can adjust colour of grid
and colour of selected objects outline. Standard MUI colour requesters are
used. Click on gadget showing current color to change it.

@{fg fill}@{b}Keyboard:@{ub}@{fg text}
Opens window with @{"keyboard shortcuts" LINK SHORTCUTS} settings.

@{fg fill}@{b}Save as defaults:@{ub}@{fg text}
Saves prefs to configuration file in ENVARC: directory. Saved values are:
- all settings from 'Display prefs' window.
- all settings from 'Layers prefs' window.
- all settings from 'Keyboard shortcuts' window.
- grid settings.

Default settings are loaded when program is started.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FAQ
                     @{fg shine}@{b} Typical problems with PCBDesigner@{fg text}@{ub}
@{b}
1. Program hangs up frequently, especially when MUIPreferences are used. @{ub}

Too small stack is probably the reason. PCBDesigner needs @{fg shine}12 kB@{fg text} of stack. If
You are running the program from icon, check the stack size by
'Icon/Information' in Workbench menu. If You run it from shell enter 'stack
12288' command first. Be careful using program launchers like ToolsDaemon,
StartMenu, TinyMeter etc. For PCBDesigner use 'run as WB program' option
(stack size will be taken from icon), or enter proper stack size.

@{b}2. When I draw tracks quickly program leaves 'place track' mode
   unexpectedly.

@{ub}Two following LMB clicks are interpreted as one doubleclick. Decrease
system doubleclick time by Input program in Prefs directory, or draw tracks
a little slower...
@ENDNODE
@NODE CONFIG "Configuration"

                     @{fg shine}@{b}Fitting PCBDesigner to Your Amiga@{fg text}@{ub}

PCBDesigner is written for comfortable use on efery Amiga, which meet hard
& soft @{"requirements" LINK Wymagania}. No matter is it A500 or A4000 with PPC. But You should
configure some options. First important thing is user interface. You can
change it using MUI Preferences program. I advise You to use an registered
version of MUI. 

@{fg shine}Screen selection@{fg text}

As for every MUI program You can select screen for PCBDesigner. It can be
Workbench or separate screen. Select screen with square pixels if You can.
PCBDesigner works even on 320x200 screen, but forget about it. 640x200 (or
better 256) is acceptable, but not comfortable. Screen should have at least
16 colours, or 8 if You don't use to many layers, and don't use MagicWB,
or similar palette (some colorus are too close). On the other hand using 256
or 128 colours on AGA machines causes PCBDesigner to work slower. Owners of
gfx-boards can of course use 256 or more colours, but true color mode really
isn't neccesary with this program...

@{fg shine}Doubleclick time@{fg text}

Doubleclick is used in PCBDesigner to terminate @{"'place track'" LINK "TOOLBAR"} mode. When
You place sections of a track quickly You can get in @{"trouble" LINK "FAQ"}. PCBDesigner
uses OS doubleclick routines, so use Input program in Prefs dir.

@{fg shine}Scrolling@{fg text}

When You  scroll edit area every visible object is redrawn. It can take up a
moment. So scroll distance was made configurable to the user. You can adjust
it choosing @{"Preferences/Display" LINK "MENUS"} menu item.

@{fg shine}Object drawing@{fg text}

In the same menu item You can select method of object drawing. The  simplest
and the fastest is 'single line'. But it's illeglible. 'Wireframe'  mode  is
the best for editing and for final drawing on slower machines. Starting from
A1200+FAST You can choose 'solid figures' for final drawing.

@{fg shine}Keyboard shortcuts@{fg text}

PCBDesigner allows You to define keyboard shortcuts.  You  can  work  faster
using keyboard instead of menus and icons. Shortcuts are user definable,  so
You can eg. set them the same as in program You are using  at  work  on  PC.
@{"Here" LINK SHORTCUTS} You'll find more about this.


@ENDNODE
@node GLOSSARY "Glossary"

@{fg fill}@{b}mils;@{fg text}@{ub} a measure unit commonly used in PCB designing. It is equal to 1/1000
of inch (0.0254 mm). 

@{fg fill}@{b}pad; @{ub}@{fg text}small area of cooper at the end of track. A pin of an electronic
component is soldered here. Typical pad is round and have a hole in centre.
Pads can be also oval, rectangular, octagonal etc. In SMD technology pads
have no holes.

@{fg fill}@{b}printed circuit board;@{fg text}@{ub} is a board usually made of glass-epoxide or paper-
phenol laminate. Cooper strips are placed on one or both sides of the board.
These strips acts as electrical conections between electronic components.
Components are soldered to strips at ends. These ends are shaped to fit
component's pins, and are called soldering pads. Pads can have holes (in
traditional technology) or not (Surface Mounted Devices - SMD).

@{fg fill}@{b}track;@{fg text}@{ub} a cooper strip on PCB, which makes an electrical connection between
two pins of electronic components. Width of a track depends mainly on
strength of electric current flowing in it.
@endnode
@node NEWS "What's new in this version?"

@{b}@{fg fill}New in 0.34 version@{ub}

@{fg text}Basic edit possibilities have been added:

- Moving objects with drag&drop.
- "rubber band" editing for tracks (wires).
- selecting objects.
- deleting objects.
- variable track width from 1 to 9999 mils.

Also:

- Saving and loading defalut settings.
- Bubble help for toolbar icons.
- User definable keyboard shortcuts.
- Improved graphics engine (special low-chipmem ellipse drawing procedure).

@endnode
@node OBJECTS "Working with objects"

@{b}Objects in PCBDesigner@{ub}

Everything placed on PCB project is an object. There are two kinds of
objects in PCBDesigner (in this version):
@{fg shine}@{b}*@{fg text}@{ub} track - is composed of one rectangle and two circles at ends. It
represents one section of physical track on PCB. 
@{fg shine}@{b}*@{fg text}@{ub} pad - soldering pad on PCB. It can be composed of a few objects. These
objects are on two special layers: pads layer and holes layer. Pads layer
represents cooper area of the pad. Holes layer represents hole. It allows
making pads with any shape of cooper and hole. However pad shape is
hardcoded in this version. This hardcoded pad consists of two circles.

@{b}Placing objects@{ub}

@{" placing pads   " LINK TOOLBAR_PADS}
@{" placing tracks " LINK TOOLBAR_TRACKS}

@{b}Selecting objects@{ub}

To select an object just click on it with LMB. It will be drawn with outline
in different colour. Another clicking deselects  the  object.  When  program
determines which object has been clicked it searches  object  list  starting
from the deepest layer, even if  clicked  point  is  covered  by  object  on
"higher" layer. When You click  on  circle  shared  by  two  or  more  track
sections on the same layer (e.g. bend point), all these sections  will  be  
selected.

@{b}Moving objects@{ub}

To move an object press LMB on it. It will be outlined. Then still  pressing
LMB drag object to its new position and release LMB. When You want  to  move
a track section don't press on ending circles.

@{b}Deleting objects@{ub}

Select object (s) as described  above.  Then  press  @{"Del" LINK SHORTCUTS}  on  keyboard.  All
selected objects will be deleted.

@{b}"Rubber band" track editing@{ub}

@{fg shine}@{b}*@{fg text}@{ub} moving bend point of track: press LMB on the point (circle) then drag it to
a new position. Release LMB.
@{fg shine}@{b}*@{fg text}@{ub}"breaking" track section into two: press LMB somewhere in the middle of the
track section @{fg fill}holding any 'Alt' key@{fg text}. Then drag two new sections. Release LMB.

@endnode
@node KEYBOARD "Using keyboard"

@{b}Standard menu shortcuts.

@{ub}Some menu items have standard system shortcuts. These are:

@{fg shine}A@{fg text} + Q   @{" Quit " LINK MENUS 11}
@{fg shine}A@{fg text} + E   @{" Save current settings as defaults " LINK MENUS 38}

Where @{fg shine}A@{fg text} is the 'right amiga' key.

@{b}Standard gadget shortcuts.@{ub}

Some button gadgets (e.g. Save/Use/Cancel in settings window) have also 
shortcuts. Just press a key with a letter which is @{u}underlined@{uu} in a gadget
text. 

@{b}Standard MUI keyboard actions.@{ub}

It works in all windows (including pop-ups). You can manipulate all  gadgets
with keyboard. Key combinations are adjustable via MUI Preferences.

@{b}User definable shortcuts@{ub}

Click @{"here" LINK SHORTCUTS}.

@endnode
@NODE SHORTCUTS "Keyboard shortcuts"

@{b}User definable keyboard shortcuts@{ub}

You can open keyboard configuration window from menu (Preferences/Keyboard).
You can type keys (or key combinations)  definitions  into  string  gadgets.
Keys  are  described  in  commodities.library  convention,   used   eg.   in
commodities programs. If any key description  is  incorrect,  error  message
will  be  displayed  and  cursor  will  be  placed  in  a  string  with  bad
description.

@ENDNODE
@node GADGETS "Gadgets"

@{b}Gadgets below the edit area:@{ub}
 
 @{" Track width " LINK TRACK_WIDTH}
 @{" Coordinates " LINK COORDINATES}

@endnode
@node TRACK_WIDTH "Track width gadget"

@{b}Track width gadget@{ub}

You can change width of placed tracks with this gadget.  Width can vary from
1 to 9999 mils.  Type desired width in the string gadget or use popup to set
one of predefined standard widths.

@endnode
@node COORDINATES "Coordinates gadget"

@{b}Coordinates gadget@{ub}

This little one shows current coodrinates of the mouse pointer.  It reflects 
snap grid settings. Of course it shows correct values only if the pointer is
over the edit area.

@endnode
